value.value: A terminology for coding of adverse reactions, developed by Hoechst in 1991.
An adverse reaction terminology created in Japan, based on the World Health Organization's Adverse Reaction Terminology.
Lowest level of the MedDRA terminology, related to a single PT as a synonym, lexical variant, or quasi-synonym.
A descriptive word or phrase selected as an authorized descriptor to represent a discrete concept.
Highest level of the MedDRA terminology, and distinguished by anatomical or physiological system, etiology, or purpose.
A superordinate descriptor for one or more MedDRA high level terms (HLT). It is subordinate to System Organ Class (SOC).

Burkitt lymphoma characterized by the presence of malignant cells with eccentric basophilic cytoplasm. The nucleoli of these cells are often single and central. This morphologic variant of Burkitt lymphoma is more often seen in patients with immunodeficiency.

value.value: An extension of the ICD-9 created by the U.S. National Center for Health Statistics so that the system could be used to capture more morbidity data. This extension included a section of procedure codes.

The central message of a communication.
A substance that is emitted or released.
Somebody or something that sends or transmits something.

An orally bioavailable receptor tyrosine kinase inhibitor with potential antineoplastic activity. AMG 706 selectively targets and inhibits vascular endothelial growth factor (VEGFR), platelet-derived growth factor (PDGFR), Kit, and Ret receptors, thereby inhibiting angiogenesis and cellular proliferation.
A diagram that shows step-by-step progression through a procedure or system especially using connecting lines and a set of conventional symbols.
The part of the name or logo associated with a specific product or service identifying and distinguishing it from varieties of the same product or service marketed by competing companies.
A list of goods or services on sale with their description and prices published as a printed document, or as an electronic document.
A class of metal-containing organic compounds, where a C atom is joined directly to the metal.
A primary or metastatic malignant neoplasm that affects the hypopharynx.
To give something back, or the getting back thereof.
Denoting individuals or tissues that are genetically identical.
Place into enforced isolation.
Occurring third in place, order, degree, value, or rank.
Denoting the area posterior to the pubic bone.
The fold of peritoneum, or mesentery, attached to the upper portion of the rectum and connecting it with the sacrum.
A grade 3 follicular lymphoma in which centrocytes are present.

Any aquatic invertebrate animal having a shell and belonging to the phylum Mollusca, the class Crustacea (phylum Arthropoda), or the phylum Echinodermata. The term is often used for the edible species of the groups, especially those that are fished or raised commercially.
A grade 3 follicular lymphoma composed of solid sheets of centroblasts.

Distributed worldwide, crustaceans are distinguished by having two pairs of antenna-like appendages in front of the mouth and other paired appendages near the mouth that act like jaws. Most species are marine, including shrimps and barnacles. Some, including crayfishes, live in freshwater habitats; others (e.g., sand fleas, land crabs, and sow bugs) live in moist terrestrial environments.
